which can be seen in one of the last TV spots of Furious 7 at the end, is 
grey! ;)

of the first F&F (in this video above) and because it was the first race 
between Dom & Brian alone... ;) 

So, in Furious 7 there are going to be two Charger's, the legendary black 
one, and another in grey.

Real Fact:  The white Supra (can also be seen in the same short seconds 
scene where the grey Charger appears) was actually Paul Walker's real car, 
it was one of his car collection that he had!

comments.text:
+Blak Nyte Then again. If you have a much a less quality car, then you can 
still win by going really aggressive. You would just have to ram your 
opponent's car every time he/she tries to pass you. Just basically keep 
them behind you at all times at a good distance. Not too far, cause they 
speed up on the side and pass. And not too close because he/she could ram 
you into the wall.But this is a one on one race example. This strategy most 
likely wouldn't work with races with more than one opponent racer. It would 
just be too much to handle.Races depend on a lot of things. The length of 
the race, opening position(such as starting of first,second,third,etc. or 
starting off equally), NOS, strategy, shift change timing, tires(in terms 
of grip) are just some. I respect your opinion though. It just really 
depends on the factors in the situation.

comments.text:
No, not you, I was referring to palmer0700's comment of "blown headgasket i 
think"

I agree with you Steven, it was a hole in the block.
Which is funny from a real life point of view. If he blew a piston through 
the block 1/2 way down the track, he wouldn't have finished keeping up with 
that Supra..
 In the movie world, the Charger has "900 horses of detroit muscle".
The supra isn't ever specified, but in real life it has about 550whp, 
without nitrous. Add the 150shot of nitrous it was running, probably over 
700whp. Vs a 900hp car that just blew a hole in the block.

These movies are great, very entertaining, but the physics are just unreal.
Like at racewars, where Jesse's Jetta (with a bolt on ABA 115hp 2.0 8v.. no 
more than 140bhp without the direct port 150hp shot of nitrous. AND it was 
an automatic) almost beat a Honda S2000, with 240hp stock, a CR 6 speed 
trans, and "a hundred grand under the hood". Such craziness.

Same with the first race. Brian's Eclipse was just a 420a, you can see it 
when Jesse pops the hood. He says it has "I see a cool air intake, a nos 
fogger system and a t4 turbo dominic, I see an AIC controller, it has 
direct port nitrous injection.. and a stand alone engine management system".
 Well, first of all, why is there a n2o fogger in the intake path if it has 
direct injection? That makes no sense. A cool air intake (really a INJEN 
cold air intake) with a t4 turbo? That makes no sense. There is no 
intercooler. The intake manifold has the "cool air intake" attached, just 
like a N/A 420a should. So the F&F Eclipse had ~150hp in real life. It was 
FWD.
The Integra GSR driven by Ja-Rule was just bolt on B18C, so no more than 
200bhp.
And Dom was driving a TT RX7.. with a sneakypete nitrous system, a veilside 
exhaust, and more.. and the Eclipse keeps up? There's no way that ever 
could have happened. There's no way the first scene with the Eclipse ever 
could have happened..140mph in a parking lot with 150hp? No way jose.

Good movies none-the-less. They're what got me into automobiles!

comments.text:
I bought mine off the showroom floor. It came into the dealer at noon and 
by 6pm it was mine! Came from the factory (I discovered later) bored out 
.10 over. When I had it rebuilt at 110K miles, we bored it out to .20, 
shaved the heads, stronger compression rings, had a 2.76 rear-end. And 
while it was an automatic and had a 3 barrel carb, I walked away from 
everything that wanted to take me on, including a same year (?) trans-am on 
the 1/4 mile. (I never told him I had a load of tar paper and shingles in 
the trunk cause we were going to the mtns to work on the cabin that weekend 
;) ) My dad was a mechanic for 40 years, and he loved his oldest daughter 
(me) and I had smaller hands and 2 of them (he lost one arm in an "unloaded 
shotgun accident") So I helped my daddy work on cars. Many a weekend as a 
divorced mom found me and a Hayes or Chilton in the driveway as I rebuilt 
master cylinders, slave cylinders, changed brake pads, re-built calipers, 
and so on. I can break down an engine and put it back together and have it 
run just fine.... at least when they were real engines and not these 
computer run tin cans. V8, V6, flat head, V4 even....
comments.author: gilliansl

comments.text: +gilliansl nice, i love them old school muscle cars =) i love the 74 Cuda

90mph and it sucks down to the road), and a 74 Cuda bored out .20 over, 
2.76 rear-end - ran like a scaled cat! See, I hung out with a bad crowd. My 
mechanic dad, and later one of the head mechanics for JLP racing and dated 
Tim Coconis (drove that ceramic engine at Indy)

comments.text:
It was early December in 2003 when I first played Need for Speed 
Underground (game inspired by F&F movie). I fell in love with that game 
soon and my friend saw that and he was like; "Man,if you love this game so 
much,why don't you check out F&F movie series?".. I was like; "Ok,I'll do 
it". I was really inspired by this movie and soon I started to play NFS 
game seriously. After that,NFS wasn't just another video game,F&F wasn't 
just a movie,Paul wasn't just my favourite actor. He changed my live. Soon 
I started to dream about that I'll get my first car some day. I never had 
goal in my life,I never had purpose in my life. Paul changed that. He is 
more then just an actor. He is an Angel. He is my Hero. Thank you Paul. We 
will all miss you. Today I'll be watching this movie again (second part 
also).. Today I will play NFS again. Just to remember and honor you! RiP 
buddy!! <3 <3﻿

comments.text:
Oh, and before you think I'm a tuner fan boy, I'm not. I love muscle cars 
to bits, but an all motor car, is a naturally aspirated engine running pump 
gas. I've been to drag strips where some of those guys run engine well over 
$40 000 bucks that pump out well over 600 horses without any NOS, Turbos, 
Super Chargers, or Race Gas. I really wish the Charger would have been 
rebuilt in the other movies properly. Instead it has really awful looking 
low profile wheels.
comments.author: Jake Hefferman

comments.text:
It's not an "all motor" really. It's a forced induction engine. What do you 
think the blower on it is connected to? A blower usually connects to a 
supercharger to help the supercharger force even more air into an engine 
than it usually does. By using the cars speed the scoop collects the air, 
forces it into the supercharger, which then forces the air into the engine 
for a much better combustion and more power per liter of fuel. 
Superchargers are belt driven and usually use twin internal screws.
comments.author: Jake Hefferman

like that, one or the other would've happened.

pushing some 700horsepower. The Skyline is about 115k(for their fastest and

why: If you pay real close attention the left turn signal went on as well, 
thats because when the car landed both of the controls around the steering 
wheel (wipers and turn signals) went down and activated the wipers and 
blinker; they went down from either both hands slipping and hitting them on 
impact or from the force of the impact itself!!! Only the stunt driver can 
clarify which one it was.
